      • SortedBufferIterator

        public SortedBufferIterator(NavigableSet<ByteBuffer> buffers,
                    Direction direction,
                    int rowWidth)
        Creates an instance using the given set of buffers, with the given direction and specified rowWidth.
        Parameters:
        buffers - the ordered set of buffers. The members of this set are expected to be ByteBuffers with rowWidth remaining bytes. The constructor does not validate this condition.
        direction - FORWARD or REVERSE
        rowWidth - the number of bytes in a row

        public final Direction getDirection()
        Description copied from class: RowIterator
        Returns the direction of the iteration. If FORWARD, then successive non-null rows returned by this instance are monotonically increasing; if REVERSE, then successive non-null rows returned by this instance are monotonically decreasing.

      • next

        public ByteBuffer next()
        Description copied from class: RowIterator
        Returns the next row, or null if at the end of the iteration. Successive invocations return monotonically increasing or decreasing rows depending on the instance's direction.
        Specified by:
        next in class RowIterator
        Returns:
        a buffer loaded with the contents of the next row (flipped and ready to read), or null if at the end of the iteration. The returned buffer may be read-only.
        See Also:
        RowIterator.next(ByteBuffer)

      • next

        public ByteBuffer next(ByteBuffer buffer)
        Description copied from class: RowIterator
        Returns the next row, or null if at the end of the iteration. This method behaves exactly like RowIterator.next() except it uses the given work buffer. Successive invocations return monotonically increasing or decreasing rows depending on the instance's direction.
        Overrides:
        next in class RowIterator
        Parameters:
        buffer - the buffer the contents of the row is written to. Its capacity must be at least rowWidth bytes.
        Returns:
        the given buffer loaded with the contents of the next row (flipped and ready to read), or null if at the end of the iteration. The base implementation just calls RowIterator.next() and copies the contents into the given buffer. If a subclass can optimize this better, it should.
        See Also:
        RowIterator.next()
